James, Cooley, and Social Media Pressures
	It is no secret that everywhere we go we are surrounded by a different environment with many different people who all have their unique personalities. William James, a psychologist in 1890 presents the idea that we act differently depending on the different situations that we are in. This is what he calls the social self and the ability to naturally form our own groups. Along with this idea, Charles Cooley, who was a sociologist in 1902 presented the idea that we see ourselves through what we think that others feel about us and our appearance Many people today might refer to this change of personality or appearance as “being fake” or just simply “playing the part.” But could we be straying farther and farther away from our true selves due to social media and all its presentations on how we should act and what we feel that others think of us?
	On social media, we are portraying ourselves similarly to others while still having a hint of our personalities within. It is very easy to customize exactly what we want others to see or know about our personal lives. Many take this very seriously considering when a name is brought up, what is the first thing most of us do? We look them up and find anything we can to create a visual in our minds of what we think that person is like.  How we are on social media or around a new friend group we just met is very different than how we would act around our family or similarly, our closest friends that we grew up with which is an example of James and his main point. Although this is normally looked at as a bad action in most people’s eyes, it is important to create these social bonds with others whom we are not as comfortable with. Similarly, how we act at our professional job plays a large role in how our boss views us which also affects our pay and our ability to buy the things that make us who we are or items that we feel we need to fit into the newest trend. 
	Social media has swept over the world in such a short amount of time and is continuing to grow at a very high rate. Many people who use social media are very easily convinced by influencers with a very high following. Whether this be through buying a product, looking a certain way, or just doing an activity the way that the influencers are doing it. Many feel a sense of importance or as if they are fitting in with societal norms by doing these activities. This way of life is like Cooley and his ideas about viewing ourselves through the eyes of others and what we feel their opinions are about us. Our likes, comments, and shares are what we feel define us and who are which is considered “looking glass” and how it influences our self-esteem. By using social media and following the tasks of influencers we are creating a sense of fitting in but are we being our true selves and embracing what we truly love as a unique individual? 
	It is very important to continue to embrace our true selves no matter what others think, but why is it so hard to do when everyone seems to be doing the same activities or looking a certain way? This is because we are viewing ourselves through what we believe others will say and think. If we are trying to post a picture on Instagram, we are thinking about the pose and what style of fashion others are posting right now as well. It’s almost as if we are embarrassed to wear or be our natural selves on social media due to fearing others' opinions. 
	In conclusion, we are continuing to perceive ourselves more and more through what we feel others think about us due to all the different forms of social media. It is a constant loop of feedback and perception that we feel defines who we are and what we stand for. We will always present ourselves just the way we feel is necessary for a certain situation and how we want others to feel about us. Although it could feel like we are straying farther away from our true selves due to influencers and wanting to be like others, we will always have the twist that makes it unique to us. Although James' ideas are just as unique as Cooley's, social media is a great way to exemplify both and show how they can tie into one idea. Overall social media will continue to shape us into the person we are supposed to be whether that is by being our true self or by following in another’s footsteps.

The Beauty Myth: How Social Media Fuels the Fire
How often do you compare yourself to others as you scroll through Instagram, Facebook, or other social media platforms? Most people could say very often, especially teenage girls and young women. By comparing their physical appearances or even fashion choices to others, young girls are falling victim to societal beauty standards and accepting them. Although social media was created with the intention of bringing people together, it has caused a lot more issues than expected. Constantly seeing other females with the “perfect” body, hair, clothes, and life can cause young girls to feel very insecure about themselves. They may even feel like something is wrong with them because they do not look like the skinny Instagram model or the pretty girl from their high school that seems to get all of the boys. This leads to negative thoughts about one’s appearance or self as a whole, and can even lead to eating disorders, anxiety, and depression. Such ideas of what the “perfect” female should look like and the obsession females have with their appearances stems from the beauty myth. As if the beauty myth was not bad enough on its own, social media makes it impossible to escape the grips of comparison while displaying unrealistic societal beauty standards.
I can personally speak to how social media has affected me in a negative way and caused me to always compare myself to others. About two years ago, at the end of my junior year of high school, I noticed that I really started paying attention to what I looked like, and what the girls I followed on Instagram looked like. I would overanalyze everything about the pictures they posted and compare their appearances to mine. Were they prettier than me? Were their stomachs flatter than mine? Did they always have some sort of cute hairstyle? Were their clothes nicer and more fashionable than mine? And much more. These thoughts started to consume me and take up way more of my time and energy than they should have. 
It is probably not a coincidence that this was happening at the same time the COVID-19 pandemic began. Since there was nothing else to do but sit at home, I was spending a lot more time on social media than I previously had been. This gave me more time to scroll and compare myself to these girls that I had never even met in real life. Were the bikini pictures they posted what they really looked like, or did they only look like that because they were posing and spent hours editing the picture? To me it did not matter and was not even something I had considered. All I was thinking was “I wish I looked like that”. After all of this started and a beach trip with my parents was quickly approaching, I decided to start working out a lot. It was not like I never exercised or did any physical activity to begin with, because it was actually quite the opposite. I played soccer from the time I was 4 years old all the way through high school, and I even ran cross country one year in addition to soccer. While most would have considered me an active person, I felt like I needed to exercise more, not for fun or for the sport I loved, but to change my body. 
I began waking up every morning during the week and going for runs in my neighborhood, then doing additional workouts in my garage. While I told my parents and friends that I was doing this to stay in shape and because, well, “the whole world is shut down so what else and I going to do?”, my motives were a little different. My goal by exercising five days a week was to become thinner. Some mornings I genuinely enjoyed my runs, while others it was the last thing I wanted to do, but I made myself go anyway. For the entire summer I ran and did at home workouts hoping to look like the girls I was always comparing myself to. 
Today I still run and workout, but my motivation has completely changed. I work out to be healthier, to see growth, and as a stress reliever; not just to lose weight and look skinnier. The reason all of this occurred in the first place is due to the beauty myth. While I had no idea at the time, I was letting social media and the beauty myth control my life. 
  The beauty myth refers to the idea that women’s value comes from their appearance and from being attractive. Societal beauty standards came into existence because of the beauty myth. Naomi Wolfe explains that the beauty myth is a result of feminism and the advancements women have made in society. Women now have a lot more freedom and power than they once did, making the beauty myth the only remaining old feminine ideology that still has serious control over women today. Wolfe also discusses how men use the beauty myth to maintain their dominance over women. If women did not feel constant pressure about their looks and feel the need to be considered beautiful by men, then men would lose their power over women. 
A common way that the beauty myth is used to control and oppress women can be seen in almost any business. When a woman works her way up to a position of authority or a high-level position, she often faces a lot of criticism. Men may make comments like, “She only got the job because of her looks” or “She’s not actually qualified she's just hot”. These comments show how deeply rooted the beauty myth is in society. Men will not be happy for a woman who has power, but if it were another male in the same position, they would likely be happy for them. When a woman holds significant power, she is attacked and ridiculed constantly because men feel threatened and jealous. Women feel they must be beautiful and fit into societal standards to be attractive and valued, but at the same time, beauty can also be used to disqualify them. Women are in a lose-lose situation because of this. 
When it came to my experience with social media causing me to feel like I needed to change the way I looked, the beauty myth was largely at play. Although my family always told me I was “skinny”, the beauty myth was telling me that I wasn’t skinny “enough”. I felt that my value was in my appearance and that I needed to change how I looked in order to prove myself to others. Looking back now, I see that by comparing myself to every girl I saw on social media, I also felt like I was competing against them. I would see someone who looked a certain way and wished that I looked like that, but at the same time I disliked them for having what I considered to be a better physical appearance than me. Women seeing other women as competition is sadly another normal aspect of society that stems from the beauty myth. Competition between women only reinforces the beauty myth and prolongs the oppression women face. Previously I was unaware that the beauty myth even existed, but now it makes sense to me why I went through the things I did. 
Ultimately, social media heavily reaffirms the beauty myth and makes it nearly impossible to not compare oneself to others, especially in the case of young girls and young women. Additionally, societal beauty standards are a result of the beauty myth and portray unrealistic expectations of what women should look like to be considered beautiful. The beauty myth causes a lot of emotional hardship for young women, and as I have personally experienced, can cause negative thoughts and views about oneself.

Who’s the Man? Identifying Hegemonic Masculinity and Defensive Othering
Defensive othering and hegemonic masculinity are two interconnected concepts that play significant roles in shaping social dynamics, particularly in the context of gender relations. While these concepts operate in distinct ways, they both contribute to the maintenance of power structures and the perpetuation of inequality. Many people may unintentionally engage in behavior that aligns with these concepts. By highlighting these concepts’ intersectionality, we can gain deeper insights into how they function and impact society. 

Defensive othering is the social process through which individuals assert their own identity and superiority by defining and marginalizing others as different or inferior. The process involves constructing and perpetuating stereotypes, prejudices, and narratives that emphasize the differences between "us" and "them," often portraying the "other" as less worthy.

The term "othering" itself stems from the idea of perceiving certain individuals or groups as fundamentally different from one's own group. This process of othering serves to reinforce social boundaries by highlighting differences and reinforcing a sense of belonging within one's own group. Defensive othering involves a defensive response to perceived threats to one's identity or superiority, prompting individuals or groups to assert their dominance over others as a means of protecting their own sense of self-worth or social status.

Hegemonic masculinity is the idealized form of masculinity within society, embodying a set of norms that are viewed as being characteristic of "real men". Hegemonic masculinity shapes gender relations and power dynamics. Hegemonic masculinity can be portrayed through traits associated with power, aggression, competitiveness, and assertiveness. It also promotes emotional stoicism, discouraging displays of vulnerability. Hegemonic masculinity promotes independence and self-reliance, with an expectation for men to be self-sufficient and avoid seeking help or support from others. 

It is defined in opposition to femininity, marginalizing qualities associated with femininity. While hegemonic masculinity may afford privileges to those who conform to its ideals, it also imposes limitations and pressures on men to adhere to narrow and restrictive gender norms. Hegemonic masculinity perpetuates gender inequality and reinforces harmful stereotypes

Despite their differences, defensive othering and hegemonic masculinity are interconnected in several ways. Firstly, both concepts rely on the construction of binary oppositions between dominant and subordinate groups. In the case of defensive othering, this binary is often framed in terms of us versus them, with the dominant group asserting its superiority over the marginalized other. Similarly, hegemonic masculinity depends on the subordination of alternative forms of masculinity and femininity, positioning itself as the normative standard against which all others are measured.

Both defensive othering and hegemonic masculinity are deeply rooted in systems of power and privilege. Defensive othering serves to uphold existing power structures by reinforcing the social hierarchies that privilege certain groups over others. Similarly, hegemonic masculinity functions to maintain male dominance and control within patriarchal societies, granting men greater access to resources, opportunities, and social status.

An example of the intersection of defensive othering and hegemonic masculinity can be found in the phenomenon of toxic masculinity and its impact on gender-based violence. Toxic masculinity refers to the adherence to rigid gender norms and expectations that emphasize aggression, dominance, and control as essential attributes of manhood. This toxic form of masculinity is often reinforced through defensive othering, as men assert their superiority over women and other marginalized genders by perpetuating harmful stereotypes and attitudes.

For example, consider a scenario in which a group of male peers engages in locker room talk, objectifying and demeaning women in sexually explicit terms. In this scenario, defensive othering is evident as the men assert their own masculinity and superiority by dehumanizing and objectifying women as sexual objects. This behavior serves to reinforce their sense of male identity and group cohesion while marginalizing and othering women as inferior and unworthy of respect.

At the same time, this scenario also reflects the influence of hegemonic masculinity, as the men conform to societal expectations of what it means to be a "real man" by asserting their dominance and control over women. The normalization of such behavior perpetuates a culture of toxic masculinity that contributes to gender-based violence and discrimination against women and other marginalized genders.

Defensive othering and hegemonic masculinity are inherently exclusionary, as they rely on the marginalization and subordination of certain groups in order to uphold the dominance of others. This not only harms those who are targeted by defensive othering and hegemonic masculinity but also reinforces harmful stereotypes and prejudices that harm society as a whole.

How the Collective Consciousness of the Education System is Corrupt
From a young age, society teaches people the belief that having an education is a requirement to being successful in life, children are told that if they want a good job they must go to college and get a degree. This is a representation of collective consciousness, a “fundamental sociological concept that refers to the set of shared beliefs, ideas, attitudes, and knowledge that are common to a social group or society” (Cole). Collective consciousness forms a sense of unity and a feeling of belonging to a group, allowing us to establish an identity. Society exerts a powerful force on everyone's beliefs, norms, and values, causing them to behave certain ways and have similar beliefs of what is valuable in life. 
Another way that the education system is corrupt is through the fact that wealthy Americans are using their money to bribe colleges into accepting their offspring. This has occurred at colleges including “Yale, Georgetown University, Stanford University, UCLA, the University of San Diego, USC, University of Texas and Wake Forest” (Reeves). The reason behind the rich doing this is the idea of collective consciousness that we have that one’s child(ren) must get into the absolute best school, which is especially common among the upper-class.
There are immoral factors that can contribute to unfair and corrupt college admissions, rather than illegal schemes. This can consist of the legacy preferences, which boosts an admission chance of the children of alumni which usually occurs in bigger, more desirable schools. “A Princeton study found that being a legacy applicant had the same effect as adding 160 SAT points” (Jones) giving the already well-off applicants an even greater advantage than that of the lower-income applicants. This shows how the upper-class have established this collective consciousness and view of themselves to where they are able to obtain more things and in turn stay successful. It was found that elite colleges such as “Duke, Yale, Stanford, and Wake Forest take more students from families in the top one percent of the income distribution than from those in the bottom sixty percent combined.” (Jones). With this statistic one can see how much more difficult it is for lower-class students to get admitted to a top tier college. How is this supposed to allow for one to break the cycle of their parents and go into a higher paying job with all odds against them? 
Weber’s focus on the structure of society was focused on elements such as class, status, and power. Weber saw class as economically determined, meaning he believed that it was split between laborers and owners. However, Weber believed that one’s status is based on noneconomic factors such as education. These two things, class, and status determined an individual’s power, which held their influence over ideas. This shows how the upper-class can obtain more power and therefore be the ideal class that we all strive to achieve. This is where we have established and built a collective consciousness that to become powerful, you must be wealthy, and to become wealthy you must get a good job, and to get a good job you must go to college. 
College is not necessarily the way to achieve a successful life, there have been many instances where people did not get a college degree and still became successful. Some of these people include Steve Jobs (founder of apple), Ellen DeGeneres (TV host), Michael Dell, Rachel Ray, Alicia Keys, and more. Having this collective belief that one must go to college to get a good job puts a lot of pressure on children at an early age. It introduces them into society's judgements and that they will be considered disappointments or looked down on. "We're saying to the kid, 'You're broken. You're defective. In some ways, these things become self-fulfilling prophecies"(Whitaker). This quote shows that society is placing these negative thoughts into the child’s head just because they do something different than the majority. This is not the answer, as a whole people should be uplifting and encouraging the upcoming generations to support their dreams and not settle for what society tells them is right. Some teachers like those who taught Steve Harvey told him he would never make it on TV, they labeled Albert Einstein as mentally handicapped, slow, and anti-social, also said that Thomas Edison was ‘too stupid to learn anything.’ Society should not be ridiculing young minds for having dreams to become something, just because it is not the social norm. 
As a society we must begin to reestablish this collective consciousness and allow our generations to come to follow their dreams and make these decisions for themselves. The education system should be asking about an individual’s hopes and dreams without shooting it down, saying it’s unattainable. The system needs to adjust and incorporate independence of the mind to allow students to flourish rather than forcing them to all learn the same things. The education system should be helping teens find their strengths and talents by having them explore and practice new things. Through cultivating experiences, the education system can help teens explore various avenues or careers that best suit their strengths. This can relate to Marx’s concept of false consciousness, which is a “condition in which the beliefs, ideals, or ideology of a person are not in the person’s own best interest” (Marx). 
An example of how the current school system is failing to foster independent thinking is shown through the parents feeling pressured to make their children conform. In an article by Elizabeth Weil, she speaks of kids being sent home with a note that suggested they be tested for a “learning difference”. One of the parents ended up getting their child tested and paid about two thousand dollars for it. After her son protested the private tutoring for a while, her and her husband abandoned it. They later came to find out that every single one of the boys in their son’s class had been referred for testing and he did not actually need it. So, what are these shared beliefs or mass consciousness that the American society has affecting the learning and education within our school system? The Fordham Institute conducted a study and reached three conclusions; “America’s view on education is incoherent, Americans don’t pay attention to their education or get involved, and much of what Americans think they know about their education policy is simply wrong” (Jones). 
Surprisingly to find, public schools have a financial incentive to diagnose children with ADHD and ADD. It’s stated that “in 1991, eligibility rules for federal education grants were changed to provide schools with $400 in annual grant money for each child diagnosed with ADHD, as a result the ADHD cases soared” (Jones). This fact shows just how corrupt the public school system can be, diagnosing children with disorders for their financial benefit. It is also said that today, more than “7,000,000 children have been labeled and registered as permanent patients of the school system” (Jones). An absurd number of children, especially males, have been diagnosed with ADHD through the school systems. This is an occurrence that should not be happening, and the education system needs to fix this as well as other issues. 
Collective consciousness is a social phenomenon, meaning that it is diffused across a whole society and has a life of its own. Through this collective consciousness that we establish, we can pass down different values, beliefs, and traditions to the upcoming generations. Collective consciousness is the result of these external social forces that course through society and that work together to create the social phenomenon of the shared set of beliefs, values, and ideas that compose it. “We, as individuals, internalize these and make the collective consciousness a reality by doing so, and we reaffirm and reproduce it by living in ways that reflect it” (Cole). This means that the collective consciousness will always be present in society if we continue to pass on these ideals to future generations, which is negatively impacting the education system. The collective belief is that a higher education is the path to obtaining a successful life. However, without clarity and conviction to back this statement up, children and teens are being mislabeled. Instead of entrusting schools to shape children from an early age, we should allow children to prosper while gaining an education. The education system has a lot to work on, especially the aspect of allowing every person, regardless of their class or status, an equal and fair opportunity to succeed. Through the adaptation of our collective consciousness, we will be able to let our future generations grow with independent minds so they can change the world.

Irving Goffman, however, introduced the theory of the front stage versus backstage self when trying to understand social interaction and perception. The front stage mainly represents the public image that an individual will present to other people intentionally. This side of the self-portrays the way we might act as a way to conform to the current social normalities and expectations of the current culture. The backstage, however, touches more on private and true self-expressions and actions where individuals feel they can act completely real and raw and get away from impression management they may deal with in front of others. This theory deals with a more fake vs. real approach when it comes to self-perception and authenticity. Even in the name itself, one might imagine the side of the self behind the curtain verses the side broadcast on stage for all to see. This theory suggests those are the two options of the self and emphasizes the skill of “reading the room”. 
 	Imagine a real-world scenario to illustrate these two theories. We will use a job interview. When applying for a job and going in for an interview, the applicant would most likely apply their front stage self by consciously picking and choosing what they decide to say, what they wear, and the demeanor with which they present themselves to impose favor on the interviewer to get the job. They will most likely discuss all their positive qualities and the positive things that they can do to meet the expectations of the job. This is an example of the social self as an individual and the way we navigate professional environments by choosing who we want to show up as and which role to play. This is also an example of front stage self. A very real possibility in this situation is that during the preparation for this, the person getting interviewed, could discuss how they feel they may not be good enough for the job and their insecurities regarding it to a friend on the phone. This shows their authentic backstage setting. In this setting, the person getting interviewed does not feel the need to impress or sway anyone and they can just show their true feelings which is also aligned with the spiritual self-concept from Williams.
In conclusion, I see accurate parts to both theories. William James’ three selves theory does a good job of not keeping self-perception into one concise real versus fake box and for that reason I feel like it’s a more inclusive and realistic way to paint out self-perception. However, Erving Goffman’s front versus backstage gives a more closed approach that only allows a fake and real self. I personally believe that there is a lot more than fake versus real, and I align more with William James' three options because it allows for the ability to be real but selective. Both theories are well thought out and do a good job of explaining perception.

Are You Reflecting or Acting
Erving Goffman has this idea that when we interact with people it is as if we are on a stage. By the word “stage” we are always putting on a performance around everyone. We might act differently in different scenarios based on evaluating the circumstance. From there we have a back stage and a front stage personality. We perform differently in front of certain people which is what separates the back from the front stage. The backstage is how we act to the people we are the closest and most comfortable with. While the front stage is the people that we put our main performance on for. 
Then we have Charles Cooley's idea of the “Looking Glass-Self” in which we view ourselves based on how we think other people see us. We use other people’s opinions and thoughts on us as a reflection of who we are. We then take those opinions and judgments to refine how we act, portraying how we want them to see us. First someone might think about what others are thinking about them. Then they might imagine what the other person’s judgement of their appearance. Lastly you react and respond based on what you think their judgements are. 
According to Goffman, when we are out in the real world searching for a job and attending a job interview we put on our front stage. Going into a job interview you want to be as professional as you can be. When you walk into the room of a job interview your mannerisms change, you say things differently and act accordingly for the situation. For example you shake their hand, you dress more professional than you would be in your back stage. You use appropriate formal etiquette and grammar, for instance you wouldn’t use any type of “slang” words to come off unprofessional. Your body language is going to change by sitting up right, your going to smile and nod your head. By doing all of these things you are putting on your front stage on because it is as if you are putting you best foot forward. 
Now I want you to think of the times that you are having a game night with your friends and family, this would be where your backstage comes out. When you are with your friends and family you might make more jokes then you would in your front stage. Let’s say you are having a game night and you win the game, you might yell, scream, jump up and down, etc. This is an example of your backstage because you wouldn’t do these types of things in your front stage. The way you dress might also be different in that you would wear more ‘comfy’ clothes like sweatpants, sweatshirts, shorts, t-shirts. Your backstage comes our with the people you are most comfortable around. Some people refer to the back stage as your comfort zone or your true self. 
You can compare the scenarios from a front stage and back stage from the moment you enter till the moment you leave. When you walk into a job interview you are most likely to shake their hand, smile, and introduce yourself. While if you walk in to you friends house to hangout you might hug them and say a more informal hello. Then during the middle of an interview you might talk in a very formal tone, good posture, and keep smiling. While if you are in the middle of hanging out with you friends you might say some dumb things or laugh a lot. Lastly by the end of your interview you would most likely get up and shake their hand and leave. If you are saying goodbye to your friends you might give them a hug good bye and talk while you are leaving. 
The looking glass self could also be portrayed in an interview. When entering the interview you start to think about what the person conducting the interview is thinking. Then from there we respond to them based on what we think their judgements are. For example if you walk into an interview you might be thinking that they think you look presentable and well respected. From there you are going to continue to answer the questions from the interview in a well presented and respectable way. We tend to think that the person conducting the interview sees us that way because that is how we want to be seen. If we think that they believe we are respectable and well presented then we are more likely to act that way. 
Lastly, another example of the looking glass self could be getting embarrassed when giving a speech. Imagine you are up on a stage or platform and you are giving a speech. When all of the sudden you look into the audience and you see some people giving you a look of disapproval. From there you are more likely to take that judgement in and you could possibly mess up your speech. We start by thinking what they are thinking about us. Therefore we might start to think that we are incompetent in our speech. Then we act upon it which might end up making us incompetent.

Capitalist Collective Consciousness
	Capitalism, in its design is one of the most controversial topics in society today with people constantly examining the pros and cons. Capitalism values labor and products differently which can fluctuate with time.  As an individual that has worked since starting high school, it is evident that humans in ourselves are commodities. To understand how capitalism works you have to understand that the commodities in our society are operated by a “free” market, which means that there is no regulation to them. 
	Karl Marx explains the concept of alienation through “Estranged labor”. In this article Marx better relates that an individual worker works for products that is not theirs because society deems it for survival. This relates to the concept of a “free” market because the labor of the worker is a commodity, the value of the work is determined by the market. Max Weber in the “Spirit of Capitalism and the Iron Cage”, relates the protestants to the modern-day society of capitalism. He proclaims that for the protestant’s capitalism was predestined because of their work ethic. This work ethic led to the “iron cage” which contributes to the “free” market by demonstrating that there is no regulation and no escape from it. Both of what Marx and Weber preached can be shown in modern day society through the minimum wage worker.
	I can relate to the capitalistic society and am familiar with how the ideology works. Being a minimum wage worker at Duck Donuts, I’ve realized that the value of the product that I produced goes fluctuates throughout the year. At the beginning of the year business is slow, because of new year resolutions and people are trying to get in shape for summer. The value of my job changes from month to month because it a mainly labor-induced job. What sets myself apart from the theories of Marx and Weber, is that I don’t work for survival in society. If that were not the case, the value of my labor would need to be higher than the exchange value that I put out. 
	In conclusion, it can be stated that through the commodity of labor, the value of a product is exclusive to the amount of effort. The relationship between the commodities makes the supply and demand for a variety of items. Along with supply and demand is the creation of a social hierarchy that promotes only individuals with high revenue value.

Graded Essay 4
	The Presentation of Self highlighted the idea that many of life’s interactions mirror a stage-actor relationship. The individual is the actor and the stage is society. Every actor presents him or herself on a stage, wether that stage be before friends, acquaintances or strangers. Goffman saw this as an extremely common situation, which everyone participate in unconsciously or consciously. In his view, behaviors were shaped around responses to performances. More specifically, other’s perceptions of us begin to form a collective impression of who we are in society.

The Beauty Myth
Beauty myths are societal standards of beauty that are based on individual cultures and can have many different elements. In every culture, however; a beauty myth describes what a certain group of people should look like. Although many different people can beautiful, the standards are always set by the dominant group in society. This generally means that men set standards for how women should look, with complete disregard to each woman’s physical or emotional strengths. Every standard is set through gender norms that have been widely accepted in that culture. There can also be many different gender norms, so depending on where or who is a part of the society, there are traits and qualities that each gender is supposed to have or develop.
In today’s United States society, all people have equal rights. This does not mean that beauty myths are no longer present. We have many standards that are expected, and only time can help this trend crumble. Since the United States is such a diverse country, with people from around the world calling it their home, there are many different standards that have prevailed. In nearly every civilization throughout history, a single group has controlled the power, which almost always has led to discrimination and “othering.” Othering and defensive othering are both ways to label some person or some group as other. If you are labeled as other, you are not only subjected to discrimination and/or oppression, but also held to different and unrealistic standards.
The term “beauty myth” was coined by Naomi Wolf in 1990. In her book, she talked about societal pressure to conform to certain beauty standards, particularly placed on women in the West. The age of new feminist ideas previously brought freedom, but Wolf argues that also brought preconceived notions of beauty standards, self-hatred, physical obsessions, terror of aging, and other “political weapons” used against women’s advancement in society. Once women gained the same rights as men, they were still thought less of, which meant that men saw a woman’s value solely based on looks, rather than their actions. This cultural shift subjected women to unrealistic standards, and men belittled women who could not achieve the beauty standards already set in place.
Women are subjected to this beauty myth, according to Naomi Wolf, as a form of retaliation or backlash against 2nd wave feminism. During this time, the objectification of women was taken to a new level with new forms of media. Men had previously controlled society, so subjecting women to these standards seemed like a natural way to gain back cultural control. For example, women felt discriminated against as they aged, while men were thought of as wise, powerful, and successful as they aged. In some areas, this type of disparity is still found today. Throughout history and various cultures, strong men battled for beautiful women. It was thought that beautiful women were the most reproductively successful, although that has never had scientific-backing. According to Naomi Wolf, male dominated institutions are fearful of strong independent women having equal freedoms, which led to more discrimination and additionally turned women against each other.
Men are also held to standards, but it has never been institutionalized in Western cultures. Toxic masculinity is a standard that has been perpetuated by men to other men, and scientists conceived the term “hegemonic masculinity” to explain this. For example, men are told they need to be strong, wealthy laborers who provide for their families while never showing emotion. Additionally, men are subjected to certain physical standards, primarily height, which can be comparable to a beauty myth, but these standards cannot be institutionalized since women are not superior to men today. Men were once legally superior to women in the United States and many countries in the West, so it is not a comparable standard. However, in the Mediterranean from around 25,000 BCE to 700 BCE, women controlled the power in their society. In this culture, powerful women controlled the economy and often had many expendable male lovers. This example would be an accurately comparable beauty myth for men, but this is an outlier over many generations and geographical locations.
I have experienced and observed many examples of the beauty myth playing out in society. There are many preconceived notions of how women are supposed to look and dress even in 2021. Growing up in the Charlotte area, I noticed how people thought my sister and my mother should act and present themselves. My mom is a strong and beautiful woman, now 51 years old, so she is experiencing the criticism from society particularly as she is aging. For the last few years, she has clearly been aging, as she should be, but rather than people complimenting her for any of her amazing qualities, she gets criticized or joked about for having new wrinkles and/or grey hair. My father on the other hand gets complimented for looking young, even though my parents are the same age. Since I was a pre-teen, I have seen a lot of discrimination in how men are treated compared to how women are treated, and even though we are all equal in today’s culture, women are still thought less of by many people. In school I would always hear my friends and classmates degrade women who were attractive by only referring to them with sexual innuendos rather than for their personality. I do not believe it is unfair to judge someone for their looks (since everyone is attracted to looks), but I do believe it is wrong if those judgements continue to name calling or discrimination. There are many beauty standards in our culture that I have been aware of, and even thought myself, but belittling anyone for traits and qualities that are completely incontrollable is unfair and only continues this trend of inequality. 
Just as I have seen beautiful women belittled, I have seen many more women discriminated against for not meeting our society’s beauty standards. If a woman is too overweight or too skinny, they were made fun of and never given the attention that “barbie doll” women got from men. If a woman does not have the most attractive smile, or even dress a certain way, they are also thought to not conform to the norms of society. No matter which facet of beauty is criticized, women almost always start with a disadvantage. Growing up with only an older sister, I also got to see many ways that young women were discriminated against, even if they are beautiful. My sister is a beautiful 24-year-old now, so three years older than me. Even though many people thought she was a good-looking girl, she was frequently targeted by toxic men who had closed minds. My sister is not the slim, blonde haired, blue-eyed model that many men expect their ideal women to look like. If she dyed her hair any color, she was criticized. If she gained any weight, she was made fun of. If she liked certain sports, like basketball and golf, she was labelled a tom-boy. My sister is very independent and has never relied on her significant other to take care of her, which has made long term relationships hard for her. Yet this quality of hers is one that I personally respect the most.
While I grew up, I was certainly picked on for not conforming to every gender norm, but since I am a man, much of that discrimination came from other men. For as long as I can remember, women have been expected to look their best in every situation, while men are not held to that same standard. Women in modern cultures are pushed to wear makeup, provocative clothing, and act “lady-like.” I went to middle school and high school with many people who did not conform to the traditional gender roles, so I frequently saw them targeted by (mostly) men who expected them to look a certain type of way. Although the beauty myth is still ongoing today, I believe that society is progressing, and women are beginning to be treated as true equals in society. Gender Inequalities of Women in The Workplace
Inequalities and discrimination within genders have persisted long throughout history in not only the United States, but around the world.  These inequalities occur in many aspects whether it be in culture, politics, or within occupation.  What all women have in common is that they can all relate to feeling some sort of discrimination and being treated unfairly, solely because of the biases that come from gender, at some point in their lives.  These inequalities between men and women have persisted within communities and throughout society for as long as anyone can remember.  While forms of discrimination can come in various forms and in various settings, one setting in particular is in the workplace.  Regardless of what that workplace is, they are all notorious for practices that involve countless forms of unfair policies towards women which affect their employment, salaries, and the length of training.  These policies, which have occurred for centuries, are too often seen as societal norms further implementing a false idea stating that men and women are not created equal.
While it is true that over the years, we, as a society, have gotten closer to achieving gender equality.  Nonetheless, it is still an imperative issue that needs to be resolved and we still have much growing to do.  Women are constantly subject to discrimination and getting the “short end of the stick” when it comes to their careers specifically.  Within this course, we learned about the endless inequalities between genders and how men and women are not treated equally.  When it comes to discrimination towards women, it would simply be a disservice to not mention those discriminatory events that occur within the walls of their workplaces.  Gender inequalities in the workplace are important to recognize because they lead to discriminatory treatment, unequal payment, and sex labeled careers.
This semester, we learned about gender and discussed many topics surrounding this module. Author of “The Beauty Myth”, Naomi Wolf, discusses in her writing that women are constantly objectified and required to uphold certain beauty standards.  Wolf begins her reading by stating “The affluent, educated, liberated women of the First World, who can enjoy freedoms unavailable to any women ever before, do not feel as free as they want to.  During the past decade, women breached the power structure; meanwhile, eating disorders rose exponentially and cosmetic surgery became the fastest-growing medical specialty” (Wolf 1990).  Wolf provides the information that proves the fact that women are notoriously expected to uphold traditional feminine values and ideas.  This expectation of upholding feminine values relates to how women are often discriminated against in their professional careers.  Wolf also presents that women struggle with confidence by expressing “It is no accident that so many potentially powerful women feel this way. We are in the midst of a violent backlash against feminism that uses images of female beauty as a political weapon against women’s advancement: the beauty myth. As a woman released themselves from the feminine mystique of domesticity, the beauty myth took over its lost ground, expanding as it waned to carry on its work of social control” (Wolf 1990). Wolf provides proof that women who are discriminated against lack confidence due to the inappropriate treatment they generally receive. Women are often inclined to be the “nurturing mother” and be the main caretaker, given no room for exploration or individuality, that of which is in plethora for men.  This assumption feeds into employers, impacting their actions on ideology to prefer hiring men over women.  The false beliefs that society has allowed employers to believe brings in an idea of women’s supposed “lack of time”.  Gender inequalities bombard every aspect of women's lives and are a huge issue in the workplace especially. Naomi Wolf helps to bring awareness to this unjust treatment. 
Women are often treated in inequitable ways in the workplace.  “Women encounter discrimination in hiring and are less likely to be perceived as capable and committed to the occupation than men” (Friedman 2015).  This discrimation comes about because of the stereotypes created in society.  Those stereotypes often perceive women as having “womanly duties” which include the idea that mothers should solely take care of the kids, cook, and clean.  On the other hand, there are also stereotypes towards men that state that the man of the house should be the “breadwinner”.  While these stereotypes have declined in the 21st century, they are still valid within occupational environments.  These assumptions that women should stay home while men make money cause the view that women have less time and commitment for higher authority jobs and that they simply are not suitable for some careers.  This is something that absolutely should not be assumed based on the gender of someone.  Because women are expected to be in charge of family care and childcare, they are often in need to take time off to do so. “Because women are more likely to anticipate interruptions in paid employment, they may be unwilling to make the long-term commitment to an employer that a position of authority often entails'' (Wolf and Fligstein 1979).  To employers, not being able to work long hours is a disadvantage, making it more likely for a man to be hired over a woman. While one should obviously be hired due to their knowledge, skill, and cooperation within the workplace, employers should not conclude these qualities based on the stereotypes of women.
For years, the gender pay gap has been a very controversial topic because many believe that it is a myth.  Regardless of some beliefs, a gender pay gap has been proven time and time again.  The gender wage gap is “cited at 77 cents to every dollar” (Friedman 2015).  This means that on average, males in the US receive twenty-three cents per dollar higher than the average female.  Although this gap has decreased overtime, it has been stable for quite some time now.  Most of this gap occurs due to factors such as job training and education, but there is still an unexplained 9% of the wage gap.  This 9% is believed to occur solely because of discrimination.  Over 50 years ago, the United States passed the Equal Pay Act, requiring that employers pay men and women equally for doing the same work.  If two employees are doing the same work, they should be paid the same, but unfortunately this is not always the case.  For example, in professional athletics, men are usually paid more than women.  This is done because men’s sports achive higher revenue, allowing them to receive higher earning.  Mariq states “90% of sports television hours have been devoted to men’s sports, whereby women’s sports are viewed as less significant for media coverage” (Marig 2020). Women’s sports can be just as engaging as men’s sports which is why the media coverage for men and women in the same sport should equal. Overall, pay should be duplicate for men and women because it should be based solely off of skill and nothing else.
We often think of specific jobs as predominantly achieved by a male or female. “Gendered organizations are workplaces where advantage and disadvantage, corrupt and control, action and emotion, meaning and identity patterned through and in terms of a distinction between male and female, masculine and feminine” (Mastracci and Arreola 2016). Gender norms have constantly been a pattern for years and is based solely on stereotypes of men and women. Like mentioned earlier career paths and pay should not be justified by gender, but by skill and hard work.  Studies show that “Women predominantly major in fields that steer them into lower-paid occupations such as humanities, education, and social sciences such as psychology, while men major in fields, such as science, engineering, and business, that lead to higher-paying jobs” (Kugler, Tinsley and Ukhaneva 2021).  This segregation is an issue causing women to be too intimidated to break the pattern of male predominant jobs.  Men are also more likely to be given positions of authority over women.  “Recent research has shown that women are much less likely than men to be in positions of authority, even when they have the same level of education and occupational status, and that this difference cannot be explained by the fact that men are more likely to be self-employed” (Wolf and Fligstein 1979).  Something must be done to create careers to be sexually unbiased.  Research shows that this process has been “stalled” and as a whole we must stop the segregation of female and male career paths.  Cross‐national research suggests that an even greater focus on men's roles and movement into historically “feminine” domains is necessary for ultimately dismantling the persistent gender gap and “installing” the gender revolution (Friedman 2015).  Because men are primarily working the higher paying jobs, they are less likely to want to be a part of the female prevalent jobs, due to the lower income.  Like Friedman stated, to “unstall” the gender revolution we must mix the genders practicing these sex labeled careers to provide a fair workspace for both genders.
Throughout history, women have been treated as “less than” in all aspects of life but particularly the workforce.  While the list of these inequalities is a lengthy one, just a few include that of unequal pay, discriminatory treatment, and sex labeled careers.  It is important to note that inequalities occur all around us.  Women and men see gender inequalities within their homes and communities every day.  Some men still see women as caregivers and responsible for the household when they need to start seeing women for who they are today.  Today's women are self-sufficient, independent, and powerful.  They are highly educated, strong, reliable, and persistent.  By keeping women from various aspects of the workforce, it is simply just a disservice to the economy.  What this issue truly boils down to is that we, collectively, men and women, need to do more to improve gender equality. By educating communities of the disparities between genders, we can break down the barriers of inequality and change societal norms.  It is time to see more women in positions of power. There should be no discrepancy towards females in the workplace, or even in life. Men and women should be observed and valued the same. Gender should not be the characteristic that defines us or separates us from our fellow coworkers.

Goffman breaks down “the self” into two main parts; the performance and the character. Before we get into the separate parts, it’s important to understand “the self” as a whole. According to Goffman, there is no “true self,” but instead it’s a consolidated illusion we’re constantly changing and putting on. “The self” provides us with the necessary resources to act suitably when presented with a stimulus. While “the self” provides us with these assets, it can also be a product of the performance we’re putting on. With that said, the performance is the production we put on and maintain while presenting ourselves to diverse audiences. The performance also varies depending on who the spectators are. For example, we typically act differently at school or work compared to when we’re with our friends. This brings us into the character, which is the outcome of the performance. “The self” includes the psychobiology of our personality whereas the character is the way we perform to leave a certain impression on people. The character allows us to control how the audience will react to us because we attempt to produce reactions as if we’re an outsider looking in. With these parts of the self-production working simultaneously, it allows us to correctly acknowledge a stimulus. 
While Goffman breaks “the self” into two parts, James divides it into four main parts; the material self, social self, spiritual self and the pure ego. James feels the total of a man’s self consists of everything he can call his. Not just his body or thoughts, but everything he physically owns and anything that gives him some type of emotion. The Material self is the physical aspects of one’s life they identify with, such as their clothes, cars, house, etc. The Social self is how peers view us and our role in a specific context. The Spiritual self consists of our beliefs or values, consistency in our reaction to stimulus and our relative emotions or behaviors. The Pure Ego is the most comfortable we can get; it’s our unseen essence and how an individual views themself. Using these four categories, James divides aspects of our personality into being a part of the “me” or the “I”. The “me” is our response to external stimuli, and how our interactions create the experience of the self. The “me” is also referred to as our social self; how we act in social situations. While the “I” is our answer to how others view us and what we’ve learned subconsciously from interactions with people. 
Between Goffman’s and James’ concepts, we’re able to use several aspects of each to reply to stimuli accordingly depending on what type of social situation we’re in. Goffman believes we adjust our behaviors to act a certain way in social settings while James feels we use our own emotions to react to an event. By using these techniques together, we can appropriate the correct response to any factors we encounter outside or inside the body. For example, social media has a huge influence on everyone, and it’s where people seek the approval of others. When anyone makes a post on social media, they first embody the performer; posting something they feel others will enjoy. Then the character and social self come into play because depending on the feedback we get; we’ll act in response to that. The character and social self are concerned with how others view us, and they generate our justification of our actions. Next comes the pure ego, which will help us connect what we’ve learned from this interaction to our past, present and future presence on social media. We may not realize it, but we’re constantly enduring social and emotional stimuli to determine our response based on how we feel others will perceive it. 
Interacting with and reacting to people is part of our day-to-day life, even if we don’t realize it. As much as humans try not to, we care about what others think of us, and we’re constantly trying to act the way we want others to perceive us. Overall, the evidence shown throughout Goffman and James’ work provides us with an appreciation for our reaction to social and emotional stimuli. Using a combination of Goffman and James’ concepts, we can better understand how we form connections with others based upon our actions.

Although this was true sometimes, it does not mean it did not offend me. This trend additionally followed me into middle school as well as high school within the friend groups I would weave through. If I would get upset from the “playful” teasing, then I would be taking it too seriously and take the fun out of the joke. This ties back to the role I played among my friend groups. My role is making silly mistakes for the purpose of others laughter and entertainment. I have accepted that this is my role and that it is this way because that is what my friends expect from me and accept me for. However, in other scenarios, such as my family and academics, playing the role of the “easy target” would be disappointing. 
	If I am performing the role of daughter, I am expected to be responsible, independent, and live up to the expectations of my older sister. In order to do these things, I have to hold myself accountable for my grades, actions, expenses, and other things that come with being grown up. This means always working hard to supply myself with money, always getting straight A’s, and handling my real-world issues on my own. This role of the put-together, smart, independent girl is far from what I experience around my friends. I am required to transform from the silly bubblehead girl to the smart and sophisticated women. Being all these things and not slipping up is very difficult and trust me, I have fallen out of character many of times before. When this happens, I get hit with an “how could you” attitude. When my role is questioned, others around me do not know how to react. When the critics does not like the performance, they will be sure to let you know in the reviews. 
	In Erving Goffman’s piece, “Presentation of Self”, he illustrates the idea of us as humans, presenting ourselves as though we are performers on a stage, and these performances make up the self. He states, “the very structure of the self can be seen in terms of how we arrange for such performances in our Anglo-American society” (Goffman). Face to face interactions give us a role to fill and stage where we preform them. We gain a sense of self and identity through social encounters and preforming these roles. “A correctly staged and preformed scene leads to audience to impute a self a preformed character” (Goffman). We take our characters very seriously because they give us a role in the social world. Therefore, living up to these expectations is very important to us. 
	We are constantly searching for meaning in our lives. Humans strive to find a place in this society. This is why we participate in collaborate meaning-making processes like religion, clubs, activist group, etc. We have seen this trend in our world for thousands of years. We appeal to the collective conscious to fit in so that we can relate to one another and give meaning to this life. We live in the ideas of narratives to give explanation to the external world and create roles for ourselves to play. With all this being said, it is only natural that we want to play our roles the best we can in order to feel fulfilled in life. 
	I feel as though I, as well as others, take my roles very seriously because without them, I feel as though I have no purpose. We strive to appeal to the standards that the social creates. Through these standards and expectations, the self emerges and is shaped through trial and tribulation. When I am with my friends, I know the type of person they expect me to portray. I know what to say, the jokes to make, and the way to act. With my family, I know how to turn myself into the responsible, academic, and mature daughter they raised me to be. I know what jokes to slide into the conversations and when to be silly at the right time, without breaking my reputation. Breaking our character means breaking our reputation, which leaves us in the world with an unfilled purpose and lack of meaning.   
	So why do we take ourselves so seriously? As described throughout this paper, it is to find and create meaning for us. We want to feel fulfilled in our interactions and contribute positive meaning to the world around us. Like we see in religion, organizations, and many other things, we want meaning to explain our purpose in this world. All of this is very understandable and reasonable ways to think. Society has engraved in our minds the type of people we are supposed to be and the characters we are expected to portray. In my own life, I demonstrate needing to find meaning within social interactions. I allow myself to play a role that I am not always comfortable with because it gives me a purpose in my friend group. In my family, I let them hold me up to higher standard because I want them to be proud of me. I need to fulfil that role the best I can in order to feel like I have meaning to them. 
	As humans, we are bound to take ourselves too seriously. This idea has been constructed and enforced by the social for a very long time. I think striving for meaning in our lives is a trend we will never break out of. However, I think instead of taking ourselves so serious in our roles, we should learn to break out of character sometimes. If we didn’t limit ourselves to what is expected of us, we can discover more about ourselves as people. Also, if we criticized less when people stepped out of their roles, everyone would feel more accepted when they cannot live up to others standards. Overall, I think we all need to be less hard on ourselves about meeting the expectations of others and ourselves. Being authentic in all circumstances may lead to a happier and better state of mind.

Harari Compared to Previous Topics
In the book 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, written by Yuval Noah Harari, there are a variety of different topics covered. These topics include discrimination, nationalism, the dubiousness of individuality, and groupthink, among other things. Many of the topics that Harari covers in his books can be related to the topics that were discussed in our class, earlier on in the semester. Some of them may complement each other well. They may also disagree with each other, and there may be contradictions between concepts. In this essay, I hope to analyze the differences and similarities between the concepts and ideas presented in 21 Lessons for the 21st Century and the ideas that we have previously learned about in this class. 
Something that Harari brings up in the “Ignorance” chapter of his book is the idea that individuality is a myth. In his words “Humans rarely think for themselves. Rather, we think in groups.” (Harari, 222). Harari says that it is humanity's ability to think as a group that has set us apart from all other species on the planet. This is called “groupthink”. To Harari, groupthink is not inherently bad, but depending on the circumstance, it can be dangerous. On one hand, humans being able to put their knowledge together has helped us to become smarter collectively. It allows us to complete complex tasks that we may not have otherwise been able to do, had we acted as individuals. However, on the other hand, groupthink can be harmful, or even detrimental. For example, imagine if someone proposed an idea that is damaging to a certain group of people. If the majority of people not belonging to that group are convinced that this idea is a fact, then it could cause them to become prejudiced towards that group. In some cases, that belief could become institutionalized, leading to generations of harm done to the group. The concept of groupthink is interesting, as it shares similarities with concepts that have been discussed earlier in the semester, while also contradicting some of the other concepts that we have learned about. The idea of groupthink has some similarities to the concept of collective consciousness, a concept that was developed by Émile Durkheim, a sociologist, in the late 1800s. The term “collective consciousness” refers to a set of shared morals, ideas, or beliefs that unify a group of people in some way. Similarly to groupthink, collective consciousness is not presented as inherently good or evil, and the benefits and drawbacks of collective consciousness can depend on the situation. Whether or not it is harmful depends on the unifying idea or moral. Much like with groupthink, if the idea is one that is oppressive and institutionalized, it can cause harm to the specific group that the idea in question targets. However, if the belief is beneficial, it could allow humanity to become more advanced in a number of ways. Although groupthink has some similarities to collective consciousness, Harari’s belief that individuality is a myth directly contradicts concepts that were discussed very early on in the semester, specifically the ideas originated by William James, Charles Horton Cooley, and George Herbert Mead, which were discussed in Module 2. William James proposed that an individual’s identity can be divided into three parts, including the spiritual, social, and material self. Charles Horton Cooley argued a similar point, putting forward that people have a “looking glass” self, in which people change the way that they behave based on how others perceive them. Finally, George Herbert Mead, similarly to James, suggests that a person’s identity is split into three parts, those being the Self, the I, and the Me. Although these three people present different interpretations of identity, they share one thing in common. They all believe that people are individuals, with different views of the world around them, and that their identities are multifaceted. However, Harari argues that because humans rarely, if ever, think as individuals, and only really think as a group, and it is because of this that individuality is a myth. The tension between these two arguments comes from their core components. Both of these arguments can be applied to many different situations, and not all of them will contradict each other. However, the argument of whether or not people can be individuals is what creates the conflict between these points. I don’t think that any one person in this argument is right or wrong. As I said before, any of these concepts could be applied to many different sets of circumstances. I think that both arguments make good points, and have validity. How applicable the argument is just depends on the situation.
In the chapter “Nationalism”, Harari discusses many aspects of nationalism. Nationalism is defined as having extreme loyalty and devotion to one’s own nation, usually to the extent of looking down upon other nations. People who are nationalists tend to look down upon other cultures, as they consider theirs to be the “right one”. When faced with other cultures or beliefs, nationalists may react negatively or aggressively. Harari describes how these behaviors start to occur, talking about how “benign patriotism morphs into chauvinistic ultranationalism. Instead of believing that my nation is unique - which is true of all nations - I might begin feeling that my nation is supreme, that I owe it my entire loyalty, and that I have no significant obligations to anyone else'' (Harari, 112). This way of thinking is described further in the chapter “Immigration”. Harari describes how “though globalization has greatly reduced cultural differences across the planet, it has simultaneously made it far easier to encounter strangers and become upset by their oddities” (Harari, 140). Nationalists that view others in this way may feel like they don’t need to respect other cultures or people different from them. They see these people as beneath them, and feel no obligation to treat them with much consideration. This way of thinking is complimentary of racism. Extreme nationalism shares many similarities with racism, and can often be the source of racism. Earlier in the semester, racism and the different ways it can manifest were discussed, especially in module 4, where job discrimination was discussed. A key example of job discrimination can be found with the Pager discriminaiton study. The study was performed by Devah Pager and Bart Bonikowski, both from Princeton University, as well as Bruce Western from Harvard University. This study addressed the question of how racial discrimination impacts the job market. The study involved a number of job applicants, all men between the ages of 22 and 26. All of the applicants presented themselves as being of the same education level, and having equal job experience. The applicants were all either Black, White, or Latino. Some of the applicants were instructed to disclose a criminal record when asked. The results show just how widespread job discriminaiton is. Among the group that included participants that didn’t have a criminal record, the white applicants had the most positive responses, with 31% of the callbacks. Latino applicants followed with 25.2% of the positive responses, and Black people had 15.2% of the positive responses. This part of the study shows how race can have an impact on the job application process. In the group that included participants who were given a criminal record, white applicants still had the highest amount of positive responses, with 17.2% of the job offers. Latino and Black participants followed with 15.4% and 13% of the positive responses respectively. Overall, this study shows that, even though progress has been made, racial discriminaiton, especially in regards to job applications, is still very much alive. The act of judging someone based on something like their race or culture is what connects job discrimination and extreme nationalism. People who participate in extreme nationalism believe that those who are different from them are less deserving of certain opportunities or rights. When an interviewer turns down an applicant based on their race, similarly to extreme nationalists, it shows that they believe that people of a certain race are less deserving of the opportunities that other people get. 
The Pager discrimination study also has similarities to another topic covered by Harari in the “Equality” chapter of his book. In this chapter, the topic of economic disparities and class discrimination are covered. Similarly, the Pager discrimination study deals with the economic effects of racism. In 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, the history of inequality is discussed. Harari describes how economic inequality can date back to the Stone Age, and talks about how some members of hunter-gatherer communities were buried with expensive jewelry and clothing, and others were buried with nothing at all. Even back then, people’s status depended on their wealth. Harari also mentions that throughout history wealth is the only thing that determines high social status, and that “throughout history the rich and the aristocracy always imagined that they had skills superior to everybody else’s, which was why they were in control. As far as we can tell, that wasn’t true” (Harari, 75). The Pager discrimination is almost like a continuation of this chapter. It shows how economic inequality has persisted into the modern day, and the ways in which it manifests. 
In conclusion, Harari’s book covers many topics that both complement and contradict topics that have been covered in the past in this class. These topics include the comparison of economic disparity in the past and modern day, the similarities between extreme nationalism and racial discrimination, and the similarities and differences between the collective consciousness, the different “selves” that make up a person’s identity, and individuality being a myth. Having many different perspectives on an issue is important, which is why it’s essential to think critically about people’s opinions. Having different views on a topic is one thing among many that makes our experiences unique.
