The issue of alienation is more significant in today's world. Workers feel disconnected from their work, products, colleagues, and even themselves due to the way production works under capitalism. This disconnection leads to feelings of powerlessness, estrangement, and a sense of being removed from society. Moreover, this feeling extends beyond economics to affect cultural aspects, contributing to a sense of being culturally adrift and losing one's identity in an increasingly globalized society. Technology plays a role in intensifying feelings of alienation today. While technology has connected people from all over the world, it has also caused division and loneliness. People may get lost in worlds and lose touch with the natural world, leading to feelings of detachment and alienation from reality.
Apart from alienation, social alienation is also widespread nowadays. Social media platforms may seem like they bring people together, but they often result in relationships that deepen feelings of loneliness and isolation. There can be pressure on individuals to present an image online, which can lead to feelings of inadequacy and disconnect from human interactions. While Domhoff's theory, Marx's idea of commodity fetishism, and the concept of alienation offer insights, they come with some limitations. Domhoff's theory might not fully acknowledge the role of individuals and social movements in challenging power structures. Critics argue that Marx's focus on commodity fetishism is too narrow, overlooking forms of oppression like those based on gender and race. Moreover, while the idea of alienation is impactful, it may not completely capture the complexities of today's socio landscape, calling for a nuanced analysis of social relationships.
In summary, Domhoffs power elite theory, Marx's concept of commodity fetishism, and the notion of alienation serve as frameworks for understanding society. By applying these perspectives to real-world scenarios, scholars and activists can deepen their insights into issues like power dynamics, exploitation, and feelings of estrangement. However, it is crucial to approach these concepts and acknowledge their limitations to develop sophisticated analyses of contemporary socio-economic realities.

When exploring the concept of alienation in today’s world, it is worth considering whether all professions involve some level of detachment. According to Marx, alienation refers to individuals feeling disconnected from the fruits of their labor, their colleagues, at work, and even themselves. In the realm of work, this feeling of alienation shows itself in forms, adding to an issue of disconnection within society.
Modern work often involves tasks and specialized roles, which can result in a feeling of monotony and detachment from the work itself. In fields, workers might find themselves doing tasks without fully grasping how their efforts contribute to the final product or service. This lack of understanding can breed feelings of alienation and disinterest.
Additionally, the hierarchical setup in workplaces can worsen this sense of alienation among employees. In these structures, decision-making power tends to be concentrated at the top, leaving lower-level employees with little autonomy and control over their tasks. This power disparity can lead to a feeling of helplessness and alienation among workers who feel cut off from decision-making processes that impact their daily work lives. Furthermore, the increase in employment situations like contracts and gig jobs has added to feelings of alienation in today's workforce. Precarious workers often lack job security, benefits, and chances for career growth, creating a sense of instability and uncertainty. The uncertainty in job security can make workers feel disconnected, trying to find stability and a sense of belonging at work.
Technology's widespread presence at work also contributes to employees feeling detached. While technology has made work more efficient, it has also increased isolation among workers. Virtual communication tools and remote work setups can hinder interactions, leading to loneliness and detachment from coworkers. Moreover, how labor is treated as a commodity under capitalism makes workers feel alienated from their work results. In a system, labor is viewed as something to be bought and sold rather than a form of self-expression or satisfaction. This commodification can lead to workers feeling dehumanized and objectified, reduced to cogs in the production wheel.
In summary, alienation seeps into aspects of work life and contributes to a broader sense of disconnection in society. Many employees experience alienation in their jobs due to tasks, hierarchical workplace structures, precarious job conditions, or technological impacts. By acknowledging and dealing with these types of disconnection, we can strive to establish work settings that are more satisfying and purposeful for everyone.

Overcoming the Urge to Reracialize by Building a Multicultural Community
How can a non-white immigrant to the United States fit in? I was born in Lebanon and moved to the United States when I was four years old, and thus I had the experience of trying to acclimate to a change in culture coupled with the attempt to make friends and fit in at school. My desire to fit in led to embarrassment concerning various aspects of myself and my life, including my skin color and my last name, which is difficult to pronounce. Furthermore, I ended up placing myself within the racial hierarchy which is in place in the U.S, striving to be considered white as a way to feel accepted. However, as I grew older, I was fortunate enough to find friends from other cultures who inspired me and gave me the courage I needed to be myself. Overall, for a non-white immigrant moving to the U.S, befriending people from other cultures is critical to oppose the pressure to place oneself and others within a racial hierarchy.
Being an only child and a relatively insecure one at that, I felt desperate to fit in and to be liked. Through my attempts to do so, I found myself attempting to repress my culture as much as possible and I tried to avoid standing out because I did not want to be labeled as “other”. As a consequence, I felt embarrassed about various aspects of myself. For instance, I would get uncomfortable when waiters at restaurants could not understand what my parents said due to their accent. Furthermore, I would wince when thinking of people struggling to pronounce my last name at awards ceremonies and when teachers would ask me to pronounce my last name. Now, I try to say it in the easiest way possible for Americans to pronounce, even though this is not how I would pronounce it in Arabic. Moreover, after moving to the U.S, I would visit Lebanon once or twice a year. In order to make the trip worthwhile over Christmas break, I would skip a few days of class and as such would be asked to make an educational presentation on my trip to Lebanon to share with the class when I returned. This would also lead to embarrassment because I was the only person in class who did such presentations. 
After the tenth grade, I went to the North Carolina School of Science and Mathematics (NCSSM), which had a far greater level of diversity and which had several multicultural events occurring throughout my time there. At NCSSM, I was not as worried about standing out because there were lots of my peers from different cultures. 
Tomás Almaguer described the process of the reracialization of Latino populations in the United States. Reracialization is when a group fuses the racial divisions and hierarchies of  their country of origin with those of the country they immigrated to; each group will position itself in relation to the other in the newly formed racial hierarchy. For example, a white immigrant from Iceland might conduct reracialization upon arriving in the U.S, thus positioning themselves higher up in the racial hierarchy than a black immigrant from Kenya. 
 I have been told that I appear ethnically ambiguous and have observed that my physical appearance and skin color are similar to those of people from various parts of the world. Moreover, I have been mistaken for a Hispanic person on multiple occasions by Hispanics. When I was little, I wished that I had a lighter skin tone so that I would appear to be more white. I thought that I was “almost” white. In the summer, I would be saddened by the fact that my skin would get darker, pushing me further away from the race I wanted to be. Thus, after I moved to the U.S., I began the process of reracialization, not only of the people I met but of myself as well. In Lebanon, race was not something I thought of because most people looked like me. Here, there is a clear racial hierarchy which pervades media and social interactions in both subtle and striking ways, placing white people on top and black people on the bottom. When growing up, I had friends, the majority of whom were white; this was due to the fact that my school was predominantly white and that I held stereotypes about the black students, which led me to avoid attempting to start friendships with them. Maybe I wanted to be accepted by white people to feed into my hope of being perceived as white. Nowadays, I feel more comfortable spending time with people who are from other cultures. Yuval Harari vs. Sociology 
In this reflection essay, my goal is to compare Yuval Harari’s arguments in 21 Lessons for the 21st Century to sociological topics from this course. In a broad sense, Harari has similar perspectives to many sociology points mentioned previously in this class, but this essay will serve as a more detailed synthesis of two differing perspectives. While Harari focuses on the 21st century and the lessons of history we should head advice from, much of sociology reveals lessons and understandings of human behavior from the past that are still relevant today. Yuval Harari is a historian and philosopher who forms his arguments to convey that type of perspective, while sociology describes  social relationships and human behavior in relation to those historical perspectives. In Yuval Harari’s book, Chapter 6’s lesson is about civilization in which he talks about community, culture, and religion in relation to historical and geographical perspectives. Going forward, I will compare this chapter to sociological perspectives on similar topics from module 1 such as “The Neurology of Religion” by Maryanski and Turner, “Microfoundations” by Fligstein and MacAdams, and “The Cultural Logic of Collective Representation” by Durkheim.
	In module 1, “The Neurology of Religion” by Maryanski and Turner describes religion not by what each individual religion believes, but rather the mechanisms that are behind the formation of religion in humans. Maryanski and Turner’s perspective comes from an evolutionary standpoint, where they identified reasons for religious expansion through diving back in history to when humans had the brain capacity for religion but did not yet collectively believe. The authors argue against recent tendencies to view religion as simple neurological forces, and instead explain religion to be a complex compilation of many driving factors. Religion does not happen because humans have a “God gene” or cognitive “nodules” in the brain to enable their capacity for religious belief. Religion may partially be caused by neurology like that, but those perspectives leave out the evolutionary reasons for religion that formed from the evolution of neurology along with cognitive and emotional dynamics. According to Maryanski and Turner, religion itself is not just belief in the supernatural; it is communities of individuals with shared beliefs of sacred and supernatural powers, engaging in emotional rituals, and organizing those rituals within social structures in the community. Religion evolved while ancient humans evolved the capacity to believe in the supernatural. No other species on Earth has the capacity for collective religious belief and that ultimately stems from human consciousness and human’s capacity to maintain social connections. Maryanski and Turner illustrate the importance of behavioral adaptations, such as stronger social groupings, that has allowed religion to have longevity in human societies.
“Microfoundations” by Fligstein and MacAdams talks about rational choice theory and the social behavior of humans compared to other primates. Humans have the capacity for abstract thought, which distinguishes them from other primates such as chimpanzees or gorillas. Humans can make things meaningful but can also make things seem meaningless. This reason explains what Fligstein and MacAdams mean when they describe human abstract thought as “double-edged.” Just as humans can find inspiration and assign meaning to our goals and achievements, we can also doubt that our lives have any meaning at all. This distinguishes us from other primates who follow their social structure and follow their natural instincts rather than draw inspiration from abstract thought. Fligstein and MacAdams coined the phrase “the existential function of the social.” According to them, the social (or society) provides coordinated, meaningful activity; allowing us to collectively make each other’s lives meaningful (or meaningless). Behavioral evolution of the human species around 45,000 years ago created the kind of humans we see today. During this time, humans developed various sorts of communication that were beneficial to survival such as language, art, and burial traditions. Humans had the capacity to do this before, but through collective meaning making projects, we began to evolve into more social creatures who assigned symbolic reality to have true meaning.
“The Cultural Logic of Collective Representation” by Durkheim illustrates the importance of religion in society. It is important to study religion in society, according to Durkheim, because shared beliefs and religions shape different societies and cultures. “Collective effervescence” refers to feeling together in society. Society and community are therefore the fundamental principles of religion. “Collective representations” are symbols, artifacts, or narratives that embody the collective beliefs and values of a group. Although these are not always religious, they certainly can be. For example, a nation’s flag is an example of a collective representation, and the ideals and values of the flag establishes some type of community. These representations are how collective consciousness manifests in society. Durkheim believes that collective ideals provide us with truth and stability. With joint individual effort and understanding, comes collective rationality and truth. Individual thoughts and experiences are variable, but when collective thought was introduced to society, impersonal thought was also unveiled. This change in human consciousness allowed for new understanding of situations and perspectives that they could have never known without communication and collective thought. This created morality in society.
	Yuval Harari speaks of religion and culture from a philosophical and historical context. For example, he mentions Orthodox Jews of today and how they refrain from images and depictions of women and girls in society and often segregate them from men and boys in their sacred spaces. Harari argues that this is a fault of some religions and cultures, because instead of adapting their collective beliefs to be inclusive in today’s standards, they uphold outdated standards from history that are not entirely accurate. According to some Orthodox Jews of today’s standards, the Jews in early Israeli history (who did not segregate people based on gender) would be blasphemous and disrespectful to their [ancient] culture… that they consider themselves to be a part of. This illustrates a blatant disregard to the cultural changes of human society that were for the better. According to Harari, humans have social systems, but they are not genetically determined. Chimpanzees and gorillas also have distinct social structures, but unlike humans, those are genetically determined. Gorillas cannot decide to behave socially as chimpanzees do, and chimpanzees cannot decide to adopt the social structure of gorillas. Both animals have the capacity for intelligent thought, but they lack the consciousness and group communication that humans have. If humans wanted to behave in social structures like chimpanzees or gorillas, we could observe the behavior of the animals and collectively communicate how we wanted to behave. Those animals are limited to their own neurology, and since humans are a more complex species, we have evolved from our ancient ancestors to behave completely different than in the past. Humans are one species but have many different cultures, beliefs, and social identifiers. People around the world speak different languages, believe in different supernatural powers, and learn from different historical outcomes. Human structures and religions constantly change, because humans can look at the recorded past and make adequate changes for the future. Other animals do not have the same cognitive abilities.
While Harari analyzes human behavior and achievement throughout history, the sociological perspectives mentioned previously find the root of that behavior and achievement. Harari criticizes human history to make a more inclusive tomorrow, while Maryanski and Turner, Fligstein and MacAdams, and Durkheim all explain the fundamental reasons for the behaviors. Harari sees the flaws of humans and points the readers in the moral right direction to correct those mistakes. Just as Fligstein and MacAdams describe abstract thought as “double-edged,” Harari reaffirms this belief in 21 Lessons for the 21st Century. Fligstein and MacAdams focus on the collective meaningful developments of humans, while Harari focuses on the contrary beliefs and the negative impacts that come from meaningless thought. Regarding religion, Harari focuses on the negatives of religion and what that conveys to society, while Maryanski and Turner focus on what led to the development of religion and what has kept religion in society. Both texts talk about the causes and effects of religion on humans, but Harari focuses on the growth that society can have, without disregarding the importance of religion. Regarding Durkheim and collective representations, Harari similarly finds the importance of collective beliefs on truth and stability. What differs between the two texts is which side of truth they are on. Durkheim reiterates how collective ideals lead to clearer beliefs in society, while Harari illustrates how collective ideals can be harmful to the overall society if not everyone shares the ideals. 
In modern society it is hard to have collective beliefs that align with everyone, but upholding beneficial beliefs is important for the future. Yuval Harari’s text combines many cultures, just as our nations of today do. The sociological ideas talked about previously mostly refer to general human behavior of the past and how that affects us today, but Yuval Harari’s specific lessons for the 21st century tie history with how we want society to look in the future. Just as Harari listed many lessons for us to learn from, we can equally learn from sociological perspectives of the past. Collectively, humans need to take Harari’s lessons and combine them with the sociological lessons from the past, to accurately understand how history continues to affect civilization today.

The sociability of humans is at the center of Mead's ideas on the self. He proposes that the self is not something innate or predetermined, but emerges through social interaction. One of Mead’s many contributions to social psychology is his concept of the “I” and the “me.” Mead refers to these two states as phases of the self. This distinction highlights the mutual exchange between individual agency and social influence in the construction of the self. There are times when the “I” emerges and creates new responses that do not align with the “Me” that has been created. The intersection of these two states occurs through reflection. 
“I” represents the spontaneous and creative aspect of the self. The “I” reflects the self as a subject of experiences. Mead describes the “I” as being a response to the “Me”. “I” is not immediately aware of itself. Imagine you’re at a dinner party with colleagues. As you engage in conversation with one of your work friends, they remind you of a funny memory. This causes you to feel the uncontrollable urge to laugh out loud. This is an example of the “I” taking precedence. You momentarily lose awareness of the social norms dictating that setting and express yourself without regard for external expectations. 
We can describe the "Me" as the objective that we experience when we reflect on our actions. While you were at that dinner party laughing loudly, you suddenly engaged in your “Me” aspect. You remembered the context of the social situation and regained your composure. You become aware of what is expected of you and make the conscious decision to suppress the urge to laugh, aligning your behavior with societal norms. “Me” is not a static state. It is a phase of your existence that is constantly transforming. 
William James, an American philosopher, produced work that contributed to the understanding of the self in a social context. Similarly to Mead, James separates the self into “Me” and “I”. However, James argues that the “Me” can be divided into subcategories- the social self, the material self, and the spiritual self. The division of the self into these categories supports both James’ and Mead’s claim that human identity is multifaceted and influenced by one’s environment and personal thoughts.  
The social self is the aspect of the self that relates to an individual’s identity with others. The social self is shaped by social interaction and the roles expected in society. For James, people act based on who they are with. For example, a person may have an entirely different personality at work than the personality they have at home with their family.
The material self relates to the physical body, possessions, and the immediate environment that surrounds someone. The possessions that compose someone's material self are tied to their identity. Things like the body, family, clothing, wealth, and other tangible possessions constitute the material self. According to James, the cornerstone of the material self rests upon the physical body. Following the body, attire holds significance. He claims that clothing serves as a way for individuals to express their perceived identity or social status, thereby contributing to the creating and maintaining one’s self-image. Furthermore, money and family play pivotal roles in the material self. The loss of a family member often results in a corresponding loss of one’s identity. A substantial financial loss could prompt a fundamental shift in an individual’s sense of self. Cell phones have grown to become large parts of a material identity. There is a large dependency on cell phones, as they have become indispensable tools for sociality. Individuals rely on their phones to stay connected with others. 
The spiritual self is the innermost core of a person’s existence. Thoughts, feelings, and consciousness make up this state of being. The spiritual self represents one’s unique identity beyond their physical and social dimensions. The spiritual self motivates reactions. Reactions are based on emotions, thoughts, and intentions. The spiritual self includes introspection and looking inward. The religious self is used to explore profound spiritual, moral, or intellectual questions free from the influence of others.
James and Mead propose that developing the self is not entirely an individual process. Both share common ground in their emphasis on the social nature of identity formation and the dynamic interplay between individuals and their social environments. The self relies heavily on social interactions. We are aware of this because of the large contributions James and Mead made to sociology.

	The Beauty Myth is a book written by Naomi Wolf in 1990 where she formulates an ideology about women and beauty. In this book she talks about the different ways that women have progressed throughout society and the ways they have fought for the rights that they have. She discusses how even though they have broken into positions of power that have not existed for women in the past, there are new issues that arise with each breakthrough. She mentions all the ways that women will tear down their bodies and go through strenuous dieting, physical activity, and surgery just to look in the mirror and see a body that pleases them. (Wolf 9) These are some of the ideas that lead her to come up with the beauty myth. She defines the beauty myth as the apparent or assumed want of women to look beautiful due to the belief that this beauty is going to lead them to more success. (Wolf 10)
	The beauty myth is both very simple and very complex and in terms of modern feminism there are different ways to look at it. History has gone through two major waves of feminism that have broken down many barriers for women, but there will always be things left to fight for. This is where the third wave of feminism can be seen in the present day. The beauty myth and Modern Feminism go hand and hand and can be looked at and applied to many ideas and modern problems. The beauty myth and its existence in society have major negative effects on Modern Feminism and the ways that women are treated. The beauty myth is seen affecting women with eating disorders and their economic effects, prescriptive beauty norms and its hierarchy, as well as feminizing and controlling women and their racial constructs. 
	In the last 30 years the rates of eating disorders and obesity in women and girls has exponentially increased to dangerous levels and the outlining reasons behind these increased rates can be tied back to the beauty myth. Well known eating disorders like anorexia nervosa and bulimia have risen roughly 3%, from 1% to 4%, in females in the United States. Rates of bulimia nervoasa in college and high school females are estimated to be about 20%, but when representative testing and sampling is done, it is closer to 5%. The likely cause of the inflation of these numbers is seen as consciousness-raising efforts brought on by Wolf’s Beauty Myth. There has also been increased rates of obesity where a very negative social stigma has been created around being overweight. (Averett 304-305) What these statistics are able to explain is the truths about the existence and severity of eating disorders and obesity in females. While numbers like 4% and 5% don’t seem exceptionally high, it means that standing in a room with 100 females, 4 of them are going to suffer from anorexia nervosa or bulimia and 5 of them suffering from bulimia nervosa. What the beauty myth has done with numbers like these is inflate them for people to see, and create a stigma around the diseases. It does this with the intention to scare women into taking better care of their body and encouraging unhealthy mindsets that ultimately cause more harm than good. 
After examining the reasons for the increased rates of eating disorders and obesity another problem can be looked at, which is the statistics that detail the economic losses that these women are suffering from due to having an eating disorder or being obese. The economic status of someone suffering from an eating disorder or someone who is obese can suffer for manny reasons both simple and complex. A simple, surface level reason is to say that these people are not physically able to work some jobs, thus preventing them from being able to work. Not to say that these people don’t exist, but when looking at the people who are perfectly able to work and are working, these people are making significantly less money. Averett says, “In employment-selectivity corrected wage equations, the pay differential is minus 12 percent for obese women and minus 5 percent for obese men.”, which shows the blatant discriminatin against obese people and even more so, obese women. (306) Averett goes on to list more specific statistics of different age groups that have suffered economic losses do to the fact that they are obese. The statistics are simple and direct and they show a direct correlation between economic losses being greater in obese women than in obese men or men and women of a standard weight class. Where the beauty myth comes into this is when you apply the definition of the beauty myth to the employers who are making these wage decisions. Employers expect that someone who is physically fit or more appealing to the eye is going to work better and is worthy of more money. The beauty myth is able to showcase that if a woman who is obese and a woman who is not obese applied for the same job with the same exact resume, then the woman who is not obese will get the job and get a hihger salary becaus her appearance gives the idea that she will be a better worker. 
Prescriptive Beauty Norms can be defined as ways that women will spend time, money, and effort to attain the level of beauty seen in society, and these norms affect many aspects of modern day feminism and do a great deal to hinder women’s progress. A lot of women have the ability to take beauty norms like dressing up and wearing makeup and genuinely enjoy them and gain a sense of empowerment from feeling beautiful and put together. It is not that easy for everyone as some women will either not have the resources, not have the money, or not have the capabilities to do these things on a regular basis. This is where the beauty norms start to be taken as disempowering as Ramati-Ziber writes, “However, when intense social pressure turns pursuing beauty into a mandate (rather than a freely chosen activity), beauty practices become socially coercive, an obligation women must fulfill or risk being “. . . deemed uncivilized and immoral”(Fredrickson & Roberts, 1997, p. 182)”. (318) The disempowerment comes when these beauty norms are being forced and not seen as an option. This broadcasts a feeling to women where they believe that they have to be fully out together to go out for the day or society is going to make negative opinions about them. The Beauty Norm is seen as the push to enjoy these norms and feel empowerment from them, but in reality the too heavy push toward empowerment turns into disempowerment. 
After defining Prescriptive Beauty Norms, also known as PBN, they can be applied to the beauty myth and the way this is done is through the built in Hierarchy-Enhancing effects of the beauty myth. In Wolf’s books she further defines the beauty myth through many different lenses and goes on to explain that it is more about types of behavior that is encouraged and not solely appearance. What this means is that there is a gender hierarchy that becomes enforced showcasing the different body types and how they are seen in society. Ramati Ziber describes the main three components of the beauty myth as, “(a) beauty ideals, which Toledano (2012) suggests include both “biological,” less easily modified, bodily standards (e.g., youth, thinness) and “performed,” more malleable, grooming standards (e.g., wearing make-up and high heels); (b) attainability beliefs, believing that beauty ideals can be reached via beauty practices; and (c) the PBN, which prescribes women to intensively strive for and prioritize attainting beauty.” (319) These different components are what push the hierarchy as each component has certain things that make someone more desirable and are going to put them higher up in the hierarchy. Someone who did not have the good traits from these components is going to be lower down on the hierarchy. The beauty myth pushes people into categories based on how many of these components they satisfy. 
Burcar analyzes the beauty myth through the lens of Toni Morrison’s The Bluest Eye and she breaks down the ways that the Myth has made gendered beauty norms into a way of feminizing and controlling women. The Bluest Eye is about a woman who decides to leave her domestic confinement and head to Hollywood To pursue a career in cinema. Being successful in Hollywood and having a career in front of a screen all comes down to if they can fit the mold of what is deemed to be beautiful, and can this beauty be used and capitalized off of. The beauty myth very obviously fits the mold of Hollywood because just like the beauty myth, in Hollywood if you are beautiful you are going to be successful and if you are not their idea of beautiful then you will not be successful. 
Bucar also analyzes the effects of the beauty myth in The Bluest Eye as it pertains to the racial constructs of beauty. Beauty in itself dissects people into who is conventionally beautiful and not beautiful, and these groups can be further broken down with race. A student from a 2016/2017 seminar provided this analysis of The Bluest Eye, “Pecola is black and because of that she is not just ugly in the eyes of Mr. Yacobowski, she is not even worth his glance. Not only was the teacher outwardly racist doward Pecola, but due to this racism he would never even consider her to be beautiful and fit into beauty norms. The beauty myth ties directly into racial constructs and people's perception of what is beautiful, and shows a further step into someone's analysis of what is beauty. 
The beauty myth can be defined many ways and throughout daily life it could be stumbled upon 100 times without even realizing it. Naomi Wolf defined the beauty myth in 1990 but that is not to say that it did not exist before. The reality is that it has likely always existed and her book in 1990 only brought to light a fraction of the way that it affects women. In the twenty-first century as society is moving through the third wave of feminism, it is the first major femenism movement since the existence of Naomi Wolf’s book. What this means is that, as modern feminists fight for more rights, equal treatment, equal respect, better wages, and more representation, the beauty myth can be dissected in these fights.  The beauty myth and its existence in society have had major negative effects on Modern waves of Feminism and the ways that women are treated. The beauty myth is seen majorly affecting women suffering from eating disorders and obesity and their economic effects, prescriptive beauty norms and the hierarchies enforced, as well as feminizing and controlling women and their racial beauty constructs.

In the mountains of North Carolina, there are about one thousand acres of land owned by two men. This place is called Turtle Island Preserve. In the summers, Turtle Island Preserve hosts summer camps for young men from the ages of ten to eighteen. These camps last two weeks and place an emphasis on the skills they teach young men about traditional survival skills. I attended these camps for four years and was exposed to a culture that I would have never found if I had not attended the camps. However, the culture which Turtle Island proudly boasts as one of inclusivity and acceptance, is much more prone to the pitfalls of hegemonic masculinity and the hierarchical pyramid of domination that accompanied this culture. 
To give you a better idea of the exact circumstances that bred this culture of hegemonic masculinity, allow me to explain the demographic that this camp typically attracted. During my four summers attending the camp, I never saw a single camper or counselor that wasn’t white. Any women that were living or working on the land were kept far away from the campers. This included them eating at different times. So while there were women living on the land during the boys two week camp, our exposure to them was limited as much as possible. All of the counselors were ex-campers that were over eighteen and therefore not technically allowed to be campers. This concoction of all male, all white campers and counselors formed a sort of singular culture within the camp that was based around hedgemonic values. 
Turtle Island Preserve challenges young men to face their fears via a set of challenges. These challenges include slaughtering pigs, running 3 miles with a mouth full of water, spending a night alone in the woods, taking a polar plunge (jumping into a freezing cold pond) at dawn, and a night hike. The camp also had trouble with campers becoming violent with one another. Nobody was ever seriously hurt but there were at least one or two fights per summer between campers. These fights were the result of campers trying to exert dominance over eachother and move up the pyramid of hedgemonic masculinity. 
When campers first arrive at Turtle Island they are exposed to a hierarchy of command and told to obey that chain of command. This included meeting all of the staff on site and learning who all of the counselors are. The campers are then divided into four groups asked to pick a speaker or leader for their group. The leader the group elects remains the leader for the rest of the camp. This would immediately cause problems within some groups because multiple people wanted to be leader. The role of leader usually fell to the oldest person in the group as they were trusted to be the most reposonible. However, having a leader become appointed based on very little to no real merit caused problems. The leaders were trusted by the counselors and would settle disputes between campers. The leaders almost always showed favoritism to their friends or the people they liked the most. 
The establishment of leaders within groups also allowed for bullying and a sort of hive mind to be born within the camp. If a camper had a weak stomach and couldn’t stand the sight of pigs blood they would be teased. If a camper was scared of the dark and had a hard time falling asleep outdoors at night they would be teased. This mentality amongst campers forced the idea of hedgemonic masculinity onto the social structure of the camp. I specifically remember a game called gladiator that we were playing during my second year. The game consists of two people standing on a log and trying to push eachother off. The last person standing on the log wins and a new challenger approaches. This game exonerated the hedgemonic value of being tough and capable of dispatching multiple opponents by yourself. However, this game led to a small selection of mostly older campers that were bigger and stronger completely dominating the younger and often smaller campers by quite literally throwing them to the ground. At the time, the game just seemed like fun. But now I know that this activity reinforced this social hierarchy predicated on how well each person fits the hedgemonic values of the camp. 
	The camp utilized this pressure to be hegemonic as a way to get young men to face their fears. One activity in particular was the most infamous for establishing who was and was not worthy of praise and respect. The activity was called the ‘night hike’, but that makes it sound too simple. It was an activity in which our counselor would march the group about a mile into the woods in a random direction and make the campers wait until the sun went down. The counselor would then confiscate any flashlights the campers had brought with them and would make the campers navigate their way back to the camp by themselves with no light. Without fail, someone would be unable to complete this task and start crying for help. Ironically, these cries were always met with snickering and comparisons to a frightened animal by the other campers. The people who could not complete this challenge were seen as weak and were often picked on for the remainder of the camp. Those who could complete the challenge without any sort of fear or hesitation were seen as brave and their social status was vaulted. So in a way, these challenges became a way for campers in less than desirable social positions to improve their status through a literal test of mental fortitude. 
	The same logic applies to the other challenges. If you couldn’t take the polar plunge you were considered a coward. If you couldn’t run three miles with a mouth full of water you were weak. If you couldn’t spend a night along in the woods alone you were deemed as lesser than those who could. So while we were learning traditional survival skills, the camp was also reinforcing this idea of independence and a toughness-over-all mentality. Those that were established as weak or less masculine than the rest of the camp were picked on relentlessly until the proved themselves in one of the challenges. Then the ridicule would switch to some other camper who was unable to complete the challenges. It was this type of toxic mindset that caused the campers to face their fears. No camper ever did these challenges out of want. They did them out of necessity and to avoid bullying by the rest of their group. So though the idea behind these challenges is a pure one, and facing your fears can be healthy, the way in which each camper’s performace dictated their status meant that people felt forced to complete the challence or suffer the consequences. 
	The hedgemonic values of being tough, independent, dominant, and brave were all taught and reinforced over and over again during my four years at Turtle Island. The survival skills were really a secondary education when you compare just how much the camp is centered around making young boys into young men. The methods may seem extreme but they work pretty well as long as you can handle the violence and bullying aspects of the method. However it’s not all bad. 
	The time I spent at Turtle Island preserve exposed me to the hedgemonic lifestyle and allowed me to understand that hierarchy in a more forgiving atmosphere than the ones I encountered later in life. I also think that similar to the boys in Rockport, the boys at Turtle Island Preserve end up forming very tightly knit friendship for the duration of their stay and leaving camp always feels more sad than it should. When you consider that most fo the camp is just one test after then other in an effort to dominate those you call friends, I’m surprised that anyone got along at all. I believe that this connection between domination and kinship comes from out biological programmedness to dominate and protect. Men want to feel valued and feel important and are willing to do abnormal things in order to earn that respect. But, on the flipside, once we prove our strength, we select others who have not proven themselves and pressure them into proving their own masculinity. 
	I know that the conditions and the activities that took place at Turtle Island may seem cruel and unusual but I agree with the author of the Rockport reading when he says that the boys ultimately benefit from their experience in this type of hedgemonic culture. Though I feel no need to create my own subculture of hedgemonic values, I think being exposed to that kind of hyper masculine system was good for me and is an integral part of who I am today. But, I’m sure not everyone that attended Turtle Island benefitted from their experience. 
The bullying was constant for those who could not prove themselves and the effects of being othered by a group of people that don’t respect you is potentially very dangerous. Looking back on it now, I feel lucky to have mostly avoided the ridicule of my cabinmates. And I feel real remorse for not standing up for people who were being bullied. The biggest downside to the hedgemonic lifestyle is the complete lack of empathy. When people are judged on skill and dominance and everything becomes a competition, the humanity of each person begins to fade. Everyone is trying to dominate each other which sadly means that someone has to be dominated. 
I think the hedgemonic lifestyle is inherently problematic and should not be the sole provider of worth in a society. Though I got through my time at Turtle Island relatively unscathed, I think it’s important to note that I have mostly rejected the hedgemonic values espoused by the camp. A lifestyle based in the domination of everyone around you can breed deep resentment and sadness. Not to mention how unhealthy it is to never let your guard down and just be comfortable in your own skin. To feel like you constantly have to prove your worth to both yourself and your peers is an incredibly stressful way to live and may lead to substance abuse later in life. Though some things can be learned from hedgemonic masculinity, relying on it as a sort of one-size-fits-all approach to being a man is dangerous and causes people to lose their humanity in chasing social recognotion.

Front Stage and Backstage Behavior and Why it Exists
Why do people feel the need to change how they act based on the situation that they are in? The feeling that one has to behave differently depending on the situation is an almost universal one. Many people will keep their true selves hidden, with their real thoughts and feelings concealed behind a facade. They can only be revealed when the person is in a private setting. But what is it that drives people to be so self-conscious? In Sociology, there is a concept that explains this type of behavior. Originated by Erving Goffman, this is known as front and back stage behavior, the study of which is sometimes called dramaturgical analysis. Goffman introduced this concept in his book ,“The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life”, published in 1956. In this book, Goffman describes social interaction between people as being similar to the interaction of roles in a theater play, which explains the front and back stage comparison. The “front stage” is the way that people behave in front of an “audience”. The audience is usually a person or a group of people. Someone may make themself seem more confident, smart, or sociable than they actually are in order to make a good impression on their audience. Backstage behavior is the opposite - it is the behavior that one exhibits when there is no one else around to see it. There is no pressure to look or act presentable, so the person is able to truly let themself relax. This concept introduces the idea that everyone has a role that they are expected to play, and failure to do so will result in humiliation and ridicule from your audience. 
The main question that I have is “why?”. Why do people feel so inclined to hide who they are? Is fitting in and playing your role really this important? What makes people so willing to change who they are just to please everyone else? One possible solution to this conundrum is impression management. Impression management, as defined by Erving Goffman in the same book that he introduced front stage and backstage behavior in, is the act of trying to present yourself or behave in a way that is considered acceptable by your audience. It is connected to front and back stage behavior, specifically front stage behavior, because it concerns the way that someone acts in front of their audience. An example of impression management could be someone making an effort to dress and speak formally when going into a job interview, even though in their day to day life they could act completely differently. The book “Impression Management Theory and Social Psychological Research” by James T. Tedeschi references a great example of impression management and why people are concerned with front stage behavior in the section “Avoiding Blame and Getting Credit” (pgs. 5-10). This section explains how many people are concerned with both getting credit for their positive actions and averting criticism for their negative actions. In figure 1.1 on page 6, the many different paths someone may take to either claim responsibility or innocence when faced with the consequences of their decisions is shown.When faced with the consequences of a poorly thought out choice, people may try to distance themselves from their actions in order to avoid punishment or blame for that action, thus avoiding any damage to their public image. They may also try to justify their actions by minimizing the impact of their outcome. When faced with the positive outcomes of a choice, someone may try to enhance the benefits of their decision to make their choice seem more admirable, or they could try to make themselves seem more responsible for the outcome. This type of impression management can be seen in our society in many different cases. For example, when someone does something harmful, they may apologize in a way that seems disingenuous. They may try to place some sort of blame on the people that they hurt with their decision by saying things like “I am sorry that you feel that way”, where the person is placing blame on the upset party for feeling hurt, rather than taking responsibility for causing the hurt. This is impression management because the person who did the harmful thing is trying to absolve themself of blame or guilt by transferring it onto another person, making them look better. This is also called blame-shifting. On page 7, the types of excuses that someone may use to preserve their self-image are listed, and they include the denial of bad intentions, lack of bodily control, and denials of agency. These are all excuses meant to distance a person from their actions. They are intended to convince others that the person who committed these actions did not have as much control over the situation as everyone thought, whether or not that is actually true. They are meant to make the person look better to their audience. 
Societal expectations are also a big reason for why front stage and backstage behavior exists. These affect both front stage and backstage behavior. One’s front stage behavior “reflects internalized norms and expectations for behavior shaped partly by the setting, the particular role one plays in it, and by one’s physical appearance” (Cole, Goffman’s Front Stage and Back Stage Behavior). Concerning the front stage, the way that people are expected to act has a lot to do with how they present themselves. For example, customer service workers are expected to be courteous to all of their customers, even the ones that are unkind to them. If they don’t fulfill this expectation, they may be met with scorn from their audience, and could lose their job. Business people are expected to be professional at all times, and in every aspect of their life, such as their speech and appearance. If they fail to do so, they too could lose their job. Students in a school are often expected by their peers to keep up with certain trends or they will be met with bullying. Clearly, a lot of importance is placed upon front stage behavior, so much so that the consequences of not playing your role can be catastrophic. Societal expectations can also influence a person’s backstage behavior. For example, a student feeling pressured to follow certain trends at school may spend their time at home organizing outfits to wear to school, or a businessman concerned with looking professional may spend the hours after his shift is done rehearsing a presentation or an interview so that he does not embarrass himself in front of his coworkers. Societal expectations can differ from culture to culture, but one thing is certain. If someone fails to adhere to expectations, then they have failed to play their role, and the results can range from humiliating to devastating. There is a lot depending just on someone playing their role, including self-esteem and employment, which could also explain why keeping front stage and backstage behavior separate is important to many.
In conclusion, front stage and backstage behavior defines how people will behave differently depending on the situation that they are in. This concept was introduced by Erving Goffman, in his book “The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life”, which used theater terms to describe social behaviors. Front stage behavior refers to how someone acts when they are in front of an “audience”. When engaging in front stage behavior, a person will often make themselves act differently in order to please their audience. Backstage behavior is the way that a person acts when no one is around to judge them. Although the person isn’t expected to think about their front stage personas at this time, many will often spend this time preparing for the next time that they are in front of an audience. There are a couple of different reasons why someone would want to hide their true selves in order to please their audience. One of those reasons is impression management. Impression management is when someone presents themself in a way that makes them seem more pleasing to the audience. There are many different ways that impression management can manifest, several of those being in reaction to an action, good or bad. Depending on the consequences of the action that they took, a person may try to overstate their responsibility in the situation, distance themself from the action overall, or justify the decisions that they made. Another reason why someone would choose to behave differently in front of an audience is societal expectations. In all different cultures, and in all different situations, people have a lot of expectations placed upon them by society. Failure to live up to these expectations could result in embarrassment or ridicule from one’s audience. Many are pushed to behave or present themselves in a certain way in order to live up to these expectations. The reasons why many want to keep their front stage and backstage separate are numerous, but they all come down to one main point - people want to look good for those who are paying them attention, just as actors want to put on a good performance for their audience.

Alienation as a Product of Rationalization
Alienation is a relatively new concept in human history. For the majority of our existence as a species, humans existed for a purpose. In our labor and work experience, we have felt connected to what we are doing, and the products produced by our labor. Our societies were not so focused on production, but rather survival. However, since the onset of the industrial revolution, humans have shifted to become a resource rather than a producer. The industrial revolution brough the introduction of rationalization. The movement towards a society that is more efficient, calculable, and predictable. This has caused humans to become detached from their work, as they only see a part of the process to the product. This essay will cover how alienation has derived from the shift to a more rationalized society.
Alienation started to become a concept with the introduction of industrialization. When the industrial revolution came into effect, people were not valued as much for their skills, but for their labor. Just their ability to work and create a product or a piece of said product. For example, factory workers. When factories were first implemented, they of course needed workers. However, they did not need specialized skills. So, men came to work in factories, but the work was not enjoyable. It did not help that labor laws were not yet invented, so the workplace was likely dangerous, as well as alienating. The reason jobs like these are alienating is because you get no say in what you would like to do. Given a required task and told to complete it. This caused the beginnings of alienation. Workers were starting to be seen as a resource of labor, rather than something of value.
The industrial revolution is a prime example of rationalization. It is the very beginnings of the concept. Societies began to move towards consumerism. This shift required products to be produced at an increasing rate and speed. This meant the necessity of a more predictable product, which would be similar or the same after each production. Assembly lines are a good example of rationalization. They produce the same exact item each time, at each station. They also cause the workers who are a part of them to feel more alienated from their job. The job an individual partakes in might be a pillar of one's self, in today’s world, as well as in past eras. The reduction of the job as meaning to an individual may cause them to feel alienated from it. 
As societies have become more rationalized and more geared towards being as efficient as possible, alienation has become more widespread. This is especially seen in capitalist economies, such as the United States. Large industries and corporations with tens of thousands of employees have taken rationalization and extracted it to its truest form. Making their products and companies as efficient and predictable as possible. To do this, however, the same is required of their employees, which are quite abundant. 
To do this, employers give employees specific tasks and guidelines which they cannot break. For example, factory or warehouse workers follow very exact schedules and rules. They often do not even see the final product of what they work towards. This may cause workers to become detached from their job. They are only being seen by large industries as sources of labor, and are not as cared for as in the past. Rationalization practiced by many large corporations has created alienation, especially in today’s world. Corporations such as Amazon, Walmart, and McDonalds are all examples of forerunners of rationalization. Amazon warehouses are another great example of rationalization, and resulting alienation of employees. Warehouses have very set rule, time clocks, conveyor belts, etc, which all run in a certain way for maximum efficiency. It is necessary for the company to survive and continue to make a massive profit. The workers, in some cases, do not feel like they matter in their job. Yes, they earn a living, however they may find no meaning in their work outside of money. Because humans want to have purpose and work, doing something you don’t want to do for someone else, for a product you will never see, can be detrimental. 
In conclusion, the continual shift and leaning into rationalization over the past several hundred years has brought forth more alienation in our capitalistic society. Starting from the industrial revolution, and the introduction of the extraction of labor from humans to today, which is a more refined version of this. Because much of our society has become so focused on efficiency and max productivity, alienation is a common byproduct. It had not been seen as frequently or at all in previous societies, because each laborer existed for their purpose. Stonemasons, blacksmiths, textile workers, artisans, all had a certain purpose and a role to fill. Today, with a very consumer-based economy, the focus is on products. Rationalization is the best way to produce products. Many laborers do not see their final product, which may cause them to be alienated from their job, which can really only be seen in more modern western societies.
